I've had this installed for a few months but didn't really use it much. Then I read the article in QST that showed the radio interface. Since my last visit Wolphi has started selling a pre-built interface and cables for $57 total. Since the cables are the hardest thing to find (and build... mini-DIN connectors are a pain!) it was worth it to me to buy his interface instead of building my own. The program itself is fairly good, but it doesn't have a scope or signal browser, just one QSO at a time. So you end up hunting around a lot. The software does seem to have an AFC which helps tuning. I live in a noisy RF environment, and it did a fairly good job of decoding even with a lot of electrical noise.  Setting the audio levels on the interface was a little difficult. There's definitely a sweet spot where you get maximum output and just a hair more will kick on the ALC. It doesn't help that Android has big steps in the volume control. But I got it working.  This will be great in the field. I have a 6V gell cell and regulator that I'm sure will run the tab for hours, making it easy for PSK31 anywhere.
I am impressed. Great job programming.  Works good without direct connection to the radio.  No ham should be without this!

My primary digital app is fldigi, but I'm constantly tweaking my portable/emergency station-in-a-bag setup and was very happy to find this app, and its siblings, for my Android Galaxy Tab 7, as I now have a complete digital station setup in a single bag, including rig (FT-857D), autotuner, battery, etc.  Since purchasing it, I've completed a couple dozen QSOs and all-in-all it works very well. Due to my tablet not having a microphone/line input jack, I must resort to positioning a headphone speaker adjacent to the built-in mic, and this does make things a bit more challenging finding the optimal balance between volume without too much distortion. Folks with Android phones that have a 4 connector handsfree headset jack or similar will fare better, I think, when conditions are less than stellar.  Kudos to Wolphi for putting PSK onto Android. Worth every penny.
